    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. one more thing, why does it have to be held by a third party specifically? why can't the buyer and seller just agree to hold it themselves or use a simpler way to transfer the money once everything is ready? feels like a lot of extra steps.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow by a third party assures neutrality and security. When buyers and sellers hold the funds themselves, there could be mistrust and potential for miscommunication or misappropriation. Escrow through a third party like a title company or an attorney, provides a trusted process that follows legally binding contracts. This method offers protections such as ensuring all necessary inspections and repairs are completed, and both parties meet the contractual obligations before funds are released. It's a form of risk management that both buyer and seller commonly agree upon for their peace of mind during this critical phase of the transaction. Simplifying the escrow process too much may compromise these standards of security, which can affect the financial safety of both parties.",
